for this panel.

02:30.120 --> 02:35.320
So the Cyber Resilience Act is a new proposal of the European Commission.

02:35.320 --> 02:42.760
It intends to improve the cybersecurity of hardware and software products.

02:42.760 --> 02:45.360
It's intended to complete a puzzle.

02:45.360 --> 02:50.280
So there's already other legislation at union level on cybersecurity.

02:50.280 --> 02:56.720
Most notably, there is the NIS directive, which has recently been reformed.

02:56.720 --> 03:00.940
The NIS directive focuses more on the users of hardware and software.

03:00.940 --> 03:06.640
So it ensures that large companies, critical infrastructure providers and so forth take

03:06.640 --> 03:10.760
security seriously, do their patches regularly and all that.

03:10.760 --> 03:15.520
But the Cyber Resilience Act now focuses on the other side, on the manufacturers of these

03:15.520 --> 03:16.520
products.

03:16.520 --> 03:22.200
And, I mean, I know that many of you are probably not dealing with policy every day, and it's

03:22.200 --> 03:25.080
particular not with European Union policy.

03:25.080 --> 03:30.800
So I've just added one slide at the very beginning to quickly explain to you what the commission

03:30.800 --> 03:34.800
is and where we are in this process and who the other players are.

03:34.800 --> 03:37.980
So yeah, this is highly simplified.

03:37.980 --> 03:42.040
It's much more complicated than that, unfortunately.

03:42.040 --> 03:47.280
So I work for the European Commission for the director general connect.

03:47.280 --> 03:52.580
It's like the director generals, they are like departments within the commission.

03:52.580 --> 03:58.960
So we mostly deal with telecommunications, internet, emerging technologies and so forth.

03:58.960 --> 04:05.360
And it is the European Commission that makes legislative proposals in the European Union.

04:05.360 --> 04:11.320
So we write the draft, and then we propose this draft to the so-called co-legislators.

04:11.320 --> 04:17.600
That's European Parliament and where you have the members of European Parliament, so parliamentarians,

04:17.600 --> 04:21.440
and the council that represents the 27 member states.

04:21.440 --> 04:26.600
And these two institutions, they analyze the commission's proposal, they come up with their

04:26.600 --> 04:32.560
own positions, and once they've done that, they negotiate with one another.

04:32.560 --> 04:38.600
And at the very end, once they agree on a common line, a common position, they adopt

04:38.600 --> 04:40.440
the text and it enters into force.

04:40.440 --> 04:41.520
It becomes a law.

04:41.520 --> 04:42.840
So this is basically how it works.

04:42.840 --> 04:44.240
It's very simplified.

04:44.240 --> 04:51.480
So our proposal came out on 15 September 2022, so in autumn.

04:51.480 --> 04:54.580
And it's now with parliament and council.

04:54.580 --> 04:56.560
Parliament has not yet started discussing it.

04:56.560 --> 05:00.360
They're still sorting out which committees will be in charge of it.

05:00.360 --> 05:02.640
But council is already at full speed.

05:02.640 --> 05:05.920
There are regular meetings every second Wednesday.

05:05.920 --> 05:09.760
The council is meeting to discuss the text proposed by the commission.

05:09.760 --> 05:11.560
So that's just for your background.

05:11.560 --> 05:16.000
And now we'll talk about the substance of the proposal.

05:16.000 --> 05:19.400
So what are we trying to achieve?

05:19.400 --> 05:25.840
So we want to reduce the number of vulnerabilities in hardware and software products.

05:25.840 --> 05:33.240
Of course we know that it's an unrealistic goal to aim for zero vulnerabilities in products.

05:33.240 --> 05:34.800
And this is what this slide represents.

05:34.800 --> 05:40.000
So the cheese represents a hardware software product filled with holes.

05:40.000 --> 05:43.360
I mean, I know not all are filled with holes, but many are.

05:43.360 --> 05:48.380
And I mean, we attempt to reduce the number of such security holes in hardware and software

05:48.380 --> 05:52.440
products through legislation.

05:52.440 --> 05:57.920
And yeah, I will just get right into the main elements of the proposal to give you an overview

05:57.920 --> 06:00.980
and then I will provide some more details.

06:00.980 --> 06:06.360
So it's all about providing cybersecurity rules for hardware and software products when

06:06.360 --> 06:07.760
they're placed on the market.

06:07.760 --> 06:12.260
So placing on the market entails that we're talking about commercial activities here.

06:12.260 --> 06:16.320
So companies that make money with hardware and software products, they will have to follow

06:16.320 --> 06:17.320
these rules.

06:17.320 --> 06:20.440
We're using a well-established framework.

06:20.440 --> 06:23.320
It's called the new legislative framework.

06:23.320 --> 06:27.880
It's been used in the past by the European Union to regulate other products such as toys

06:27.880 --> 06:31.060
or machinery or electrical equipment.

06:31.060 --> 06:34.520
And you may not know it, but you're all actually very familiar with it.

06:34.520 --> 06:39.980
So whenever you see a product that has the CE marking on it, CE, I will show it later,

06:39.980 --> 06:44.640
like you have it, for example, on laptops or iPhone chargers and such things.

06:44.640 --> 06:49.220
So this is all new legislative framework regulation then.

06:49.220 --> 06:54.520
What we do in the proposal is we establish obligations for three types of economic operators

06:54.520 --> 06:55.520
for the manufacturers.

06:55.520 --> 06:58.960
I mean, that's the core element, of course, of the proposal.

06:58.960 --> 07:01.080
But then there are also the distributors.

07:01.080 --> 07:06.880
These are brick and mortar stores, online shops, and also importers that place products

07:06.880 --> 07:10.400
on the European market that have been developed in third countries.

07:10.400 --> 07:14.600
And the importers and the distributors, they don't have to, I mean, they don't do secure

07:14.600 --> 07:15.600
coding, of course.

07:15.600 --> 07:19.480
They're just selling products, but they have to ensure that the products that they are

07:19.480 --> 07:27.280
selling are, like, in line, I mean, that they comply with the Cyber Resilience Act.

07:27.280 --> 07:34.600
One of the core novelties of our proposal is that it does not just cover rules for the

07:34.600 --> 07:38.960
placing on the market, so what the product should look like, but it also covers the period

07:38.960 --> 07:41.120
after that, the entire life cycle.

07:41.120 --> 07:43.840
So I mean, you all know that for cybersecurity.

07:43.840 --> 07:48.920
It's extremely important that you keep tracking your products, that you ensure that when you

07:48.920 --> 07:53.000
discover new vulnerabilities, that you fix them, you mitigate them, you provide patches

07:53.000 --> 07:54.240
and so forth.

07:54.240 --> 07:58.720
And this is part of our proposal that for a period of five years after the placing on

07:58.720 --> 08:00.760
the market of a product, you do that.

08:00.760 --> 08:04.160
You provide security updates.

08:04.160 --> 08:10.480
One essential element of any new legislative framework regulation is harmonized standards.

08:10.480 --> 08:16.960
So the rules that we propose in the Cyber Resilience Act, they are very high level, technology

08:16.960 --> 08:19.240
neutral, objective oriented.

08:19.240 --> 08:22.160
I mean, if you go through the proposal, you will see they are really high level.

08:22.160 --> 08:31.360
It's more like on the level of provide a secure by default configuration, take care of access

08:31.360 --> 08:36.760
management, make sure data is handled confidentially and so forth.

08:36.760 --> 08:43.880
So really high level, but then we have the standards that will be developed by the European

08:43.880 --> 08:45.920
Standardization Organizations.

08:45.920 --> 08:46.920
You may have heard of them.

08:46.920 --> 08:49.840
They are called SANS-ANILAC and ETSI.

08:49.840 --> 08:52.040
And they are voluntary.

08:52.040 --> 08:57.500
You don't need to use these standards, but they will help you write secure products.

08:57.500 --> 09:01.360
And then there is also the conformity assessment.

09:01.360 --> 09:06.040
So manufacturers, they will have to demonstrate that their products are actually compliant,

09:06.040 --> 09:08.840
but I will explain that in more detail later.

09:08.840 --> 09:10.520
And finally, there is the market surveillance.

09:10.520 --> 09:14.600
So in all the member states, you will have authorities that can check out the products

09:14.600 --> 09:22.000
and approach manufacturers, ask them to remediate vulnerabilities, eliminate risks, and if they

09:22.000 --> 09:26.560
don't comply, even hand out fines.

09:26.560 --> 09:33.740
So the scope of the proposal, it's hardware and software products, products, not services.

09:33.740 --> 09:39.000
So when I say hardware products and software products, I mean final products such as laptops

09:39.000 --> 09:47.920
or operating systems, but also components such as CPUs, hard drives, software libraries,

09:47.920 --> 09:50.060
and so forth.

09:50.060 --> 09:52.460
We don't regulate services.

09:52.460 --> 09:55.600
So software as a service is outside the scope of this proposal.

09:55.600 --> 09:59.640
That's already regulated by the NIS directive, which I mentioned earlier.

09:59.640 --> 10:04.560
But we do regulate something that we call remote data processing solutions.

10:04.560 --> 10:09.940
So often today, products, they actually come with some cloud or other elements such as

10:09.940 --> 10:12.200
many mobile applications.

10:12.200 --> 10:16.480
They usually they access data in the cloud, and these are essential functionalities of

10:16.480 --> 10:17.840
the program.

10:17.840 --> 10:23.620
And then you would also have to ensure the security of these remote data processing solutions.

10:23.620 --> 10:27.120
As I already explained, we only regulate commercial products.

10:27.120 --> 10:31.960
So anything that is non-commercial is outside the scope, including open source when it's

10:31.960 --> 10:33.380
non-commercial.

10:33.380 --> 10:37.320
But on the other hand, open source that is commercial, I mean there are a lot of large

10:37.320 --> 10:42.320
commercial projects, I'm sure you're aware of them, they would be covered.

10:42.320 --> 10:46.160
And then we exclude certain products that are already regulated by other regulations

10:46.160 --> 10:48.520
such as cars or medical devices.

10:48.520 --> 10:54.800
Yeah, I mean why did we choose to exclude non-commercial open source software from the

10:54.800 --> 10:55.800
scope?

10:55.800 --> 10:59.880
Well, there are a few reasons, and first of all, this is standard practice for any new

10:59.880 --> 11:03.740
legislative framework product regulation at union level.

11:03.740 --> 11:07.040
We only focus on commercial activities.

11:07.040 --> 11:10.920
But also in the case of open source, there are some more special considerations that

11:10.920 --> 11:11.920
we took.

11:11.920 --> 11:17.520
So first of all, would it be fair to regulate someone that does not make a profit with a

11:17.520 --> 11:18.520
product, right?

11:18.520 --> 11:19.600
I mean, and we think it would not.

11:19.600 --> 11:24.280
And wouldn't we be setting the wrong incentives to regulate someone who doesn't make money

11:24.280 --> 11:25.280
with it, right?

11:25.280 --> 11:31.160
Would you keep developing something if you're asked to like follow regulation and you're

11:31.160 --> 11:32.640
not even earning money with it?

11:32.640 --> 11:36.840
So we would be setting the wrong incentives, that's why we decided to exclude them.

11:36.840 --> 11:40.920
And then of course we also know that open source, I mean, it's critical often from a

11:40.920 --> 11:46.720
cybersecurity perspective, but it's just as critical from an innovation and growth perspective.

11:46.720 --> 11:52.320
I mean, there are so many small companies, medium-sized companies that use your components,

11:52.320 --> 11:57.320
your products, free of charge to develop on top other products and services.

11:57.320 --> 12:01.440
And for them it's crucial that they have access to this resource.

12:01.440 --> 12:04.440
And that's, I mean, we are fully aware of that.

12:04.440 --> 12:10.500
And my colleague, Rice, he will, I mean, he will later on the panel also explain to you

12:10.500 --> 12:17.200
in how many other ways we support open source as the European Commission.

12:17.200 --> 12:21.840
So here in a nutshell, the obligations that manufacturers of commercial products would

12:21.840 --> 12:24.080
have to comply with.

12:24.080 --> 12:28.820
I mean, first you do a risk assessment of your product during the design phase.

12:28.820 --> 12:33.560
Then you comply with the essential requirements that are in the regulation.

12:33.560 --> 12:39.040
I explained earlier what they look like, these high-level objective-oriented requirements.

12:39.040 --> 12:44.400
Then you establish vulnerability handling processes such as a coordinated vulnerability

12:44.400 --> 12:47.440
disclosure policy.

12:47.440 --> 12:51.960
And yeah, of course, I mean, with any legislation you will have to document in which way you

12:51.960 --> 12:53.480
comply.

12:53.480 --> 12:56.960
This would be called a technical file.

12:56.960 --> 13:00.320
And once you've done all that, once you've done the conformity assessment, you can affix

13:00.320 --> 13:02.540
the CE marking to your product.

13:02.540 --> 13:07.720
And then for a period of five years, you will be required to handle the vulnerabilities

13:07.720 --> 13:10.840
that arise in your products.

13:10.840 --> 13:15.960
On top of that, there's also an obligation to report critical vulnerabilities to our

13:15.960 --> 13:18.080
cybersecurity agency.

13:18.080 --> 13:22.440
We are talking about vulnerabilities that are already exploited in the wild by criminal

13:22.440 --> 13:26.920
actors, but that have not been necessarily fixed.

13:26.920 --> 13:33.320
And this is for the purpose of helping national authorities mitigate risks in critical infrastructure

13:33.320 --> 13:36.240
and so forth.

13:36.240 --> 13:39.640
Here's one example of how we are also trying to help the community.

13:39.640 --> 13:45.440
So in the Article 11, which is about the reporting requirements for manufacturers, we require

13:45.440 --> 13:49.920
them whenever they integrate a component and they discover a vulnerability in it, and this

13:49.920 --> 13:55.760
could be an open source component, that they notify the entity or the person that maintains

13:55.760 --> 13:56.760
this component.

13:56.760 --> 13:59.140
I mean, so people like you often, for example.

13:59.140 --> 14:03.680
So for example, when you go from GitHub, when you source a component and then you discover

14:03.680 --> 14:08.760
a vulnerability, at least you should reach out to the maintainer and inform them of the

14:08.760 --> 14:09.760
vulnerability.

14:09.760 --> 14:11.400
Ideally do more.

14:11.400 --> 14:15.040
Maybe even provide code to fix it.

14:15.040 --> 14:18.820
So here is how it works as regards components.

14:18.820 --> 14:24.360
This is an example of a smartphone manufacturer that builds a smartphone.

14:24.360 --> 14:25.440
So there will be some components.

14:25.440 --> 14:28.920
Here you see them on the left-hand side in blue.

14:28.920 --> 14:32.720
These are components that the manufacturer develops themselves.

14:32.720 --> 14:38.160
So they would not be placed on the market separately, but as part of the final product.

14:38.160 --> 14:42.340
And then for these components, you would not need to do a separate conformity assessment,

14:42.340 --> 14:44.760
but it would be part of the final product.

14:44.760 --> 14:46.040
But then there are other components.

14:46.040 --> 14:51.120
You see them on the right-hand side, such as the ones that are developed by upstream

14:51.120 --> 14:52.120
manufacturers.

14:52.120 --> 14:54.120
So here you see the RAM or the CPU.

14:54.120 --> 14:57.280
In that example, it would be manufactured by someone else.

14:57.280 --> 15:01.960
So these are placed on the market separately, and it would be the upstream manufacturer

15:01.960 --> 15:07.160
who would need to ensure the security of these components and to fix the CE marking.

15:07.160 --> 15:11.620
And of course, the manufacturer of the smartphone is responsible for the entire product, right?

15:11.620 --> 15:15.040
Just because you integrate a component of someone else doesn't mean you don't take

15:15.040 --> 15:21.240
any responsibility for it, but you would need to do due diligence when you integrate those

15:21.240 --> 15:22.400
components.

15:22.400 --> 15:28.560
Yeah, so these are the categories for the conformity assessment that we propose.

15:28.560 --> 15:35.500
For the vast majority of products, the default category, you would do the conformity assessment

15:35.500 --> 15:37.160
yourself as a manufacturer.

15:37.160 --> 15:40.240
You do not need to interact with any third party.

15:40.240 --> 15:43.680
But then there is a smaller list of critical products, which you can find in the annex

15:43.680 --> 15:45.360
of our proposal.

15:45.360 --> 15:48.220
That's roughly 10% of the scope.

15:48.220 --> 15:52.840
And there we require more stringent conformity assessment and sometimes even independent

15:52.840 --> 15:55.080
third party assessment.

15:55.080 --> 16:00.320
Examples of these more critical products are firewalls, CPUs, or operating systems.

16:00.320 --> 16:04.760
And then there is also a possibility for highly critical products.

16:04.760 --> 16:11.480
We are not making use of that now, but we are proposing that in the future we can add

16:11.480 --> 16:16.960
highly critical products to a list for which it would be necessary to undergo a mandatory

16:16.960 --> 16:18.300
certification.

16:18.300 --> 16:19.920
We do not have any products in mind.

16:19.920 --> 16:25.520
This is really just to future-proof the legislation because we all know that digital products

16:25.520 --> 16:29.400
permeate society more and more and we become more and more dependent on them.

16:29.400 --> 16:34.200
And there may be a point at which we will rely on such crucial products that we need

16:34.200 --> 16:36.800
even a higher level of assurance.

16:36.800 --> 16:40.280
I don't know, think human brain interfaces or something like that.

16:40.280 --> 16:41.520
I mean, yeah.

16:41.520 --> 16:42.520
Okay.

16:42.520 --> 16:46.840
This is the CE marking that you're all very familiar with.

16:46.840 --> 16:51.480
We are also trying to facilitate compliance for the manufacturers as much as possible.

16:51.480 --> 16:56.880
So we would be providing after the entry into force of the proposal compliance on how to

16:56.880 --> 17:05.600
– sorry – guidance on compliance in general, as well as examples how to do things in practice,

17:05.600 --> 17:10.760
for example, on how to delineate what is a commercial product, what is a non-commercial

17:10.760 --> 17:11.760
product.

17:11.760 --> 17:16.840
We will also, I mean, as I said, develop these harmonized standards.

17:16.840 --> 17:20.760
We are looking into providing funding through the Digital Europe Program – that's a European

17:20.760 --> 17:25.760
funding initiative – for national market surveillance authorities, but also for manufacturers

17:25.760 --> 17:27.620
to help them comply.

17:27.620 --> 17:34.080
But then, frankly, we are also counting on you, on the community, on software developers,

17:34.080 --> 17:38.840
on the market also, to come up with tools that can help facilitate compliance.

17:38.840 --> 17:42.880
I mean, many of these tools already exist, of course, such as static and dynamic code

17:42.880 --> 17:49.200
analysis tools, S-bomb generators, but, I mean, you name it, there can be any number

17:49.200 --> 17:54.320
of tools that could help facilitate compliance, maybe to generate some of the documentation

17:54.320 --> 18:00.080
automatically and, I mean, also be extremely open to ideas how to facilitate this, so feel

18:00.080 --> 18:04.800
free to approach me after the panel and we can discuss it.

18:04.800 --> 18:10.400
Here, this is the timeline, just for you to better understand, and this is also my last

18:10.400 --> 18:11.400
slide.

18:11.400 --> 18:15.200
So, as I said, we made the proposal on 15 September.

18:15.200 --> 18:17.920
We are now undergoing this legislative process.

18:17.920 --> 18:23.700
We are hoping to conclude it before the European elections in May 2024.

18:23.700 --> 18:28.600
And then, once it's done and enters into force, we will launch a request for standardisation

18:28.600 --> 18:31.520
with the European standardisation bodies.

18:31.520 --> 18:36.520
And then, 24 months later, it would enter into application, so that's when manufacturers

18:36.520 --> 18:41.320
would need to comply with the rules and also when the harmonised standards would become

18:41.320 --> 18:42.320
available.

18:42.320 --> 18:48.480
Yeah, so there's still plenty of time for you to help within the process, to reach out

18:48.480 --> 18:53.840
to members of Parliament if you have concern or to the member state authorities and get

18:53.840 --> 18:54.840
involved.

18:54.840 --> 18:59.240
We are, of course, also extremely interested in your views, so you can also reach out to

18:59.240 --> 19:00.240
us.

19:00.240 --> 19:03.320
I mean, I also brought some business parts, so later, if you're interested, you can have

19:03.320 --> 19:04.320
some.

19:04.320 --> 19:07.680
And, yeah, I mean, I'm extremely looking forward to the discussion now.

19:07.680 --> 19:08.680
Thanks.

19:08.680 --> 19:11.560
Sorry for being so fast, but I only have 15 minutes.

19:11.560 --> 19:12.560
Thank you, Benjamin.

19:12.560 --> 19:22.400
So, I don't know if you saw me moving around during the talk, but we were discussing cyber

19:22.400 --> 19:26.800
resilience and also potential software defect.

19:26.800 --> 19:33.040
I just escorted a bug outside how convenient it was, so saving a bug.

19:33.040 --> 19:43.240
So now we're transitioning to Martin from NLNet Labs and he's going to give us his point

19:43.240 --> 19:53.120
of view of the CRA based on from an NGO, so a non-government agency or office, organisation,

19:53.120 --> 19:54.200
sorry.

19:54.200 --> 19:59.000
So this is a different approach.

19:59.000 --> 20:06.840
And, yeah, they are dealing with DNS, so that might be an important infrastructure element

20:06.840 --> 20:10.720
to consider in this topic.

20:10.720 --> 20:19.800
One more come from Martin, please.

20:19.800 --> 20:20.800
Good morning, everyone.

20:20.800 --> 20:27.360
So, I'm really grateful that Benjamin just did the hard work of explaining the legislation

20:27.360 --> 20:33.560
and for me the, I suppose, easier part of reacting to it.

20:33.560 --> 20:35.880
So my name is Martin Arzter.

20:35.880 --> 20:42.080
I work for NLNet Labs, which is a non-profit R&D organisation.

20:42.080 --> 20:45.320
We make open source software for the internet.

20:45.320 --> 20:51.040
I stole this terminology from a great report from quite a while ago.

20:51.040 --> 20:57.080
And what we do is we develop internet standards or we contribute to the development of internet

20:57.080 --> 21:01.080
standards and we make implementations.

21:01.080 --> 21:05.040
And the specific area of focus that we have...

21:05.040 --> 21:10.440
The mic closer to you.

21:10.440 --> 21:14.040
I will...

21:14.040 --> 21:18.600
So the specific work that we do is we develop, we contribute to the development of internet

21:18.600 --> 21:24.000
standards and we make implementations in software that are open source.

21:24.000 --> 21:26.320
And we've been doing this for two decades.

21:26.320 --> 21:32.680
We make software in the areas of DNS and we make software in the area of routing, specifically

21:32.680 --> 21:33.880
routing safety.

21:33.880 --> 21:38.840
And what we also do is we try to bring that knowledge to policymakers and that's what

21:38.840 --> 21:44.400
I'm doing hopefully today.

21:44.400 --> 21:50.120
So Benjamin just talked about the scoping and he mentioned that most of us would be

21:50.120 --> 21:52.040
out of scope.

21:52.040 --> 21:57.560
And when I read the proposal in September, October, I wasn't so sure.

21:57.560 --> 21:59.920
And I think that's something we should discuss.

21:59.920 --> 22:07.560
So there is a recital in the text that basically reads free and open source software should

22:07.560 --> 22:14.800
not be covered by this regulation, which is I think we should be very happy that the Commission

22:14.800 --> 22:24.320
is aware of open source and has taken concern to actually address this in new legislation

22:24.320 --> 22:25.880
that they come up with.

22:25.880 --> 22:31.720
I think that is something we should celebrate much like the fact that open source has been

22:31.720 --> 22:33.120
here for 25 years.

22:33.120 --> 22:39.520
So maybe a little warm round of applause just to acknowledge that we've been heard.

22:39.520 --> 22:46.320
And what I want to talk about today is the fact that there's a clause here and it says

22:46.320 --> 22:50.320
outside the course of a commercial activity.

22:50.320 --> 22:52.480
And what is a commercial activity?

22:52.480 --> 22:53.640
There are some examples.

22:53.640 --> 22:56.120
It's not a defined term.

22:56.120 --> 23:00.880
And one of the examples that is relevant to my organization, to Nellet Labs, is specifically

23:00.880 --> 23:06.840
that what is called out is that if you charge a price for technical support services, then

23:06.840 --> 23:09.040
you are considered commercial.

23:09.040 --> 23:12.280
So the organization I work for is a registered charity.

23:12.280 --> 23:17.440
We make software, we develop standards, we give it away for free, we give away updates

23:17.440 --> 23:19.080
for free.

23:19.080 --> 23:21.860
And yet we employ people with mortgages.

23:21.860 --> 23:25.280
So the question is how are we supposed to make money?

23:25.280 --> 23:32.380
And we found a way, namely the network operators that use our software want it to be available

23:32.380 --> 23:33.380
long term.

23:33.380 --> 23:36.920
And they want there to be different implementations available.

23:36.920 --> 23:42.140
So they've chosen to pay us to provide support.

23:42.140 --> 23:48.640
And so this makes our work a commercial activity, at least in the way we read this text.

23:48.640 --> 23:53.400
I would be glad to be wrong about most of the slides I'm showing you today.

23:53.400 --> 23:55.560
And please tell me if I am.

23:55.560 --> 24:01.240
But that's why we got interested in this legislation.

24:01.240 --> 24:08.020
And there are some risks if you look at this exception, because if you have an expansive

24:08.020 --> 24:13.400
interpretation of the word commercial, then the exception is narrow.

24:13.400 --> 24:16.840
It's this balance, right, depending on how you interpret commercial.

24:16.840 --> 24:23.120
And if it's a narrow scope of exception, then what you create is a disincentive for open

24:23.120 --> 24:29.040
source developers who start working on something in their free time to professionalize.

24:29.040 --> 24:35.920
Because at some point when you hit this commercial qualifier, then you come into scope of regulation.

24:35.920 --> 24:41.260
And there's nothing bad about regulation per se, but we have to acknowledge that the step

24:41.260 --> 24:46.840
from not being regulated to be regulated is a change, right?

24:46.840 --> 24:51.920
And what we don't want to happen is for charities like an elite labs and others who make this

24:51.920 --> 24:58.160
kind of software to realize that the way they've been able to sustain their development is

24:58.160 --> 25:00.440
now disappearing.

25:00.440 --> 25:07.000
So what we don't want is for there to be an incentive to move to closed source software.

25:07.000 --> 25:12.280
And finally, especially in the area of DNS, what we want is product diversity.

25:12.280 --> 25:21.280
So it's not a good outcome if we go to a place where there's less organizations working on

25:21.280 --> 25:26.360
these projects, because with what we want is different implementations that do not share

25:26.360 --> 25:29.920
code for stability.

25:29.920 --> 25:31.480
So it's not just me.

25:31.480 --> 25:36.440
The OSI reacted to the response, and they said, and I like this quote a lot, the problem

25:36.440 --> 25:39.760
is not the lack of taxonomy of commercial.

25:39.760 --> 25:44.160
So the solution is not explaining what commercial is supposed to be.

25:44.160 --> 25:49.280
It is the very act of making commercial the qualification rather than deployment for trade.

25:49.280 --> 25:56.240
And what is relevant about this quote is that there's a very different, the act of maintaining

25:56.240 --> 26:02.680
and creating software, and the cost of that is very distinct from the act of profiting

26:02.680 --> 26:04.280
from its deployment.

26:04.280 --> 26:10.040
And if you confuse these two steps, then you and commercial may help you confuse those

26:10.040 --> 26:14.840
steps, then we get into this place.

26:14.840 --> 26:16.800
So that's about general scoping issues.

26:16.800 --> 26:23.200
I'd like now to move to specific concerns we have from an elite labs.

26:23.200 --> 26:24.800
And why do we have concerns?

26:24.800 --> 26:31.080
Because we have products, we make unbound the resolver, we make some other product.

26:31.080 --> 26:36.920
At least we believe it's not an unreasonable interpretation to consider the stuff we release,

26:36.920 --> 26:39.040
including binaries, to be products.

26:39.040 --> 26:40.200
And maybe we're wrong.

26:40.200 --> 26:42.320
I'd love to hear that.

26:42.320 --> 26:47.040
So if we are product, and if what we do is considered commercial, then there are some

26:47.040 --> 26:52.400
unintended consequences by being covered by this legislation.

26:52.400 --> 26:59.640
Because currently we are an outfit with 15 people, 14 of whom are either software engineers

26:59.640 --> 27:03.320
or developers.

27:03.320 --> 27:10.440
Every effort we put into proving that we're doing the right thing, the compliance bit,

27:10.440 --> 27:17.480
which is a logical part of any legislation, every effort that we spend on compliance will

27:17.480 --> 27:20.600
not be spent on securing our software.

27:20.600 --> 27:26.360
And the only reason why a charity like ours exists is making secure software, resilient

27:26.360 --> 27:30.200
software for internet infrastructure.

27:30.200 --> 27:37.360
And if you look at the annex three list of critical products, it doesn't take too much

27:37.360 --> 27:45.280
imagination to frame most of what we do as critical products in terms of this legislation.

27:45.280 --> 27:52.400
And I think Benjamin explained about the way to avoid having to call in third party auditors.

27:52.400 --> 27:57.800
But it depends on the availability of European standards that are applicable to our work.

27:57.800 --> 28:04.160
And in general, I think most of us are not engaged in the European policy process.

28:04.160 --> 28:09.320
And even less of us are involved at the European standards institutions.

28:09.320 --> 28:12.760
Because basically we have no need to be there at this point in time.

28:12.760 --> 28:15.080
And we have not had a need in the past.

28:15.080 --> 28:19.000
So at an outlet we work quite a lot on standardization.

28:19.000 --> 28:24.960
But it's at multi stakeholder forms, accessible to any party without payment, et cetera.

28:24.960 --> 28:30.320
And that's not how these European standardization institutions work, unfortunately.

28:30.320 --> 28:35.240
So the escape hatch, if you are a critical product, to not have to call in third party

28:35.240 --> 28:39.060
auditors may not actually be available in practice.

28:39.060 --> 28:46.440
And that means we will have a costly burden checking our processes, which does not actually

28:46.440 --> 28:48.920
contribute to the quality of code.

28:48.920 --> 28:54.960
And that's why I think this is a concern for us, or at least an unintended consequence.

28:54.960 --> 29:00.000
There's also text in there which requires you to fix all known vulnerabilities.

29:00.000 --> 29:03.920
And this does not have a regard for severity.

29:03.920 --> 29:09.680
And what this does is if you have to fix all known vulnerabilities, then this skews your

29:09.680 --> 29:15.020
engineering effort from practices that protect you against unknown vulnerabilities.

29:15.020 --> 29:19.400
So this is this I think this is not what it was actually intended.

29:19.400 --> 29:20.800
I'm just flagging it.

29:20.800 --> 29:24.280
Because we I think we want there to be good laws.

29:24.280 --> 29:28.040
And we want to help in a democracy to achieve those good laws.

29:28.040 --> 29:33.880
I mean, why if you live in a democracy and you like that, why not contribute, I suppose.

29:33.880 --> 29:38.240
Otherwise, there's not a lot of points.

29:38.240 --> 29:41.560
So there's also more detailed concerns.

29:41.560 --> 29:48.720
So for example, we currently have the opportunity to provide security updates to providers we

29:48.720 --> 29:52.120
know are extremely critical to the functioning of the Internet.

29:52.120 --> 29:57.760
So if we are about to release a patch and give full information about what it fixes,

29:57.760 --> 30:05.820
we can choose to provide a update just ahead of time to a, for example, root server operator

30:05.820 --> 30:12.480
or some other entity which is not equal in terms of importance to all of society.

30:12.480 --> 30:17.640
And the current text takes away our ability to do so because it requires us to do everything

30:17.640 --> 30:25.780
at the same time, which may not actually benefit security, which is the goal.

30:25.780 --> 30:31.280
There's also obligations to report incidents that actually relate to third party use of

30:31.280 --> 30:32.480
our software.

30:32.480 --> 30:35.360
So we don't do any operations.

30:35.360 --> 30:36.720
We just develop software.

30:36.720 --> 30:42.000
But if we are obliged to report incidents that relate to the use of our software, this

30:42.000 --> 30:47.480
gets into a conflict of our role of remediating vulnerabilities.

30:47.480 --> 30:53.160
And this is the case because these third parties may have some reason not to go public with

30:53.160 --> 30:54.920
an incident at first.

30:54.920 --> 31:01.840
If you create a conflict of interest in talking to us, then we may need longer to fix the

31:01.840 --> 31:06.480
vulnerability if there is such a thing.

31:06.480 --> 31:14.280
What we don't know, and this is more of an uncertainty, we don't know what constitutes

31:14.280 --> 31:16.440
substantial modification.

31:16.440 --> 31:23.360
So the whole idea that you trigger reassessment of your product for the CE marking, it hinges

31:23.360 --> 31:29.200
on the fact that when substantial modification is made, you need to do it again.

31:29.200 --> 31:33.920
And we currently don't know if that's a major release, minor release, patch release.

31:33.920 --> 31:37.280
We do quite a lot of releases.

31:37.280 --> 31:43.520
And depending on how this pans out, we may spend a lot of work doing compliance and less

31:43.520 --> 31:46.640
work of doing release engineering.

31:46.640 --> 31:54.600
Finally, there is some clause about time limited availability of software for testing purposes.

31:54.600 --> 31:59.240
I think that's fundamentally incompatible with how open source is done.

31:59.240 --> 32:04.760
Much of the points I've made today, we worked on together with ISE, the authors of Bind,

32:04.760 --> 32:06.560
among others.

32:06.560 --> 32:13.160
And on their website, you can download about 30 years of binaries, of all versions of Bind

32:13.160 --> 32:18.880
ever made, which is really helpful if you're trying to find issues, vulnerabilities, whatever

32:18.880 --> 32:21.120
you try to.

32:21.120 --> 32:23.640
But the...

32:23.640 --> 32:29.120
So what we don't want is for them to have to get this stuff offline, because I don't

32:29.120 --> 32:34.320
think it actually helps us reduce vulnerabilities.

32:34.320 --> 32:39.640
So if you are interested in this stuff, I recommend you to read further, because this

32:39.640 --> 32:45.880
was just my perspective, and Elnett Labs as a charity employing people that are getting

32:45.880 --> 32:51.560
paid full time to develop open source software is not very common, and I realize that.

32:51.560 --> 32:53.080
But you don't have to take it from me.

32:53.080 --> 32:56.240
You can also read about other responses.

32:56.240 --> 33:05.200
So there's the work of OSI, there's work by Open Forum Europe, Brussels-based think tank

33:05.200 --> 33:10.680
which collects voices from other organizations relating to open source, including commercial

33:10.680 --> 33:11.720
ones.

33:11.720 --> 33:17.040
And Simon, who's in the front here, maybe he can raise his hand, actually compiled a

33:17.040 --> 33:20.080
list of responses by other...

33:20.080 --> 33:25.720
So you can take a look yourself and have a...

33:25.720 --> 33:27.120
And give it some thought.

33:27.120 --> 33:32.560
I wanted also to quickly give a shout out to a blog written by Thomas DePierre.

33:32.560 --> 33:35.440
I'm hoping I'm not butchering your name.

33:35.440 --> 33:40.280
And it relates to supply chain thinking, how that's currently quite dominant in thinking

33:40.280 --> 33:42.520
about security for open source.

33:42.520 --> 33:49.480
And his point is basically supply chain thinking doesn't work if someone in this supply chain

33:49.480 --> 33:54.200
is not actually considering themselves to be a supplier.

33:54.200 --> 33:57.720
So that's it with respect to what I had to say.

33:57.720 --> 34:02.760
In summary, we believe that these goals that the Commission is trying to achieve are worthy

34:02.760 --> 34:03.760
goals.

34:03.760 --> 34:06.800
And as a consumer, I would like them to succeed.

34:06.800 --> 34:11.800
However, there's also some unintended consequences in their current proposal.

34:11.800 --> 34:18.360
And I think we should aim as a society to fix those.

34:18.360 --> 34:21.480
I'm very interested to hear your perspective.

34:21.480 --> 34:24.040
And for now, I'd like to thank you for your attention.

34:24.040 --> 34:26.040
And I'm looking forward to the panel.

34:26.040 --> 34:28.040
Thank you.

