35:34.320 --> 35:39.600
So for the cyber resilience act, we are applying the same principle as for any other union

35:39.600 --> 35:43.880
legislation that is about services or products.

35:43.880 --> 35:48.400
So whenever you provide a service or a product in the European Union, you have to comply

35:48.400 --> 35:50.680
with the rules of the European Union.

35:50.680 --> 35:56.560
So that means for the cyber resilience act, if you provide a hardware or software manufactured

35:56.560 --> 36:02.000
outside the European Union to consumers or other users within the Union, you would have

36:02.000 --> 36:04.000
to comply with the cyber resilience act.

36:04.000 --> 36:05.800
So there's absolutely no difference.

36:05.800 --> 36:07.480
It doesn't matter where you're located.

36:07.480 --> 36:11.240
If you want to sell your products here, then you have to comply.

36:11.240 --> 36:17.920
So there's also no risk that there would be an advantage for maybe manufacturers from

36:17.920 --> 36:22.280
America or so forth that they would not have to comply and therefore have lower costs.

36:22.280 --> 36:25.040
No, it's an elite level playing field.

36:25.040 --> 36:29.080
Everyone who wants to sell their products here would have to comply with the same rules.

36:29.080 --> 36:33.360
I hope that answers your question.

36:33.360 --> 36:51.360
Hi, why is policy the right place to put these measures into effect rather than a standardization's

36:51.360 --> 36:59.560
body like ISO, which already does a lot of the same things and provides people who want

36:59.560 --> 37:14.160
the guarantees associated with this reliability testing to select products that comply with

37:14.160 --> 37:16.880
the ISO requirements?

37:16.880 --> 37:23.360
Okay, if I understood the question, the question is why we think that a mandatory approach

37:23.360 --> 37:25.200
is necessary, right?

37:25.200 --> 37:26.200
Right.

37:26.200 --> 37:36.040
Why is the mandatory approach necessary instead of a voluntary approach that could be selected

37:36.040 --> 37:38.600
by consumers who want it?

37:38.600 --> 37:43.440
Yeah, I mean, the voluntary approach is the approach that we took basically for the last

37:43.440 --> 37:45.800
20 years, right?

37:45.800 --> 37:46.800
And it hasn't worked.

37:46.800 --> 37:51.200
I mean, we are not eager to regulate new sectors.

37:51.200 --> 37:57.200
I mean, especially when it comes to such innovation and growth fostering sectors such as hardware

37:57.200 --> 37:58.200
and software.

37:58.200 --> 38:01.600
So, I mean, that's one of the reasons why the Commission of the European Union for a

38:01.600 --> 38:04.680
long time decided not to regulate.

38:04.680 --> 38:11.640
But we see that, you know, despite of new standards coming out, development of lots

38:11.640 --> 38:21.760
of secure development, lifecycle, guidance, new programming languages that are memory

38:21.760 --> 38:23.160
safe, I mean, all this is coming.

38:23.160 --> 38:24.160
We see that.

38:24.160 --> 38:28.000
But nonetheless, I mean, the vulnerabilities, they are not going down.

38:28.000 --> 38:32.000
And we see actually more cybersecurity incidents than ever before.

38:32.000 --> 38:34.080
And this is why we chose to regulate.

38:34.080 --> 38:41.040
I mean, in our view, there is simply not sufficient incentive for the market to take cybersecurity

38:41.040 --> 38:43.040
as seriously as it should.

38:43.040 --> 38:45.280
I mean, you all know this.

38:45.280 --> 38:51.280
I mean, you have so many specific features in this market such as time to market.

38:51.280 --> 38:55.480
I mean, first mover advantage, who is the first one to build a platform wins basically

38:55.480 --> 38:56.480
the whole market.

38:56.480 --> 38:57.480
Yeah.

38:57.480 --> 39:02.320
So, under all these constraints, manufacturers do not have an incentive to prioritize cybersecurity.

39:02.320 --> 39:06.920
And we feel that this can only be fixed through regulation.

39:06.920 --> 39:07.920
Thank you.

