40:11.560 --> 40:17.720
I'm going to try to not use too much legal terms because I think now we're going to enter

40:17.720 --> 40:23.080
a zone that if you're not a lawyer, you will not really understand what we're talking about.

40:23.080 --> 40:26.680
So I will kind of try to use more simple situations.

40:26.680 --> 40:32.960
I think the name of the proposal speaks by itself, Product Liability Directive.

40:32.960 --> 40:37.760
The PLD, as we call it, is about the liability.

40:37.760 --> 40:41.520
So I'm going to tell you, give you some examples.

40:41.520 --> 40:46.800
Boeing 737 Max, two of them crashed some years ago.

40:46.800 --> 40:52.240
An autonomous vehicle that crashed and killed a person.

40:52.240 --> 41:03.480
In South Korea, a lawnmower that went into a person, your mobile phone that overheats.

41:03.480 --> 41:07.760
All of these situations are what we call the liability.

41:07.760 --> 41:11.840
And all of them include softwares.

41:11.840 --> 41:16.560
So what Benjamin explained to you are the obligation that when you want to place your

41:16.560 --> 41:22.200
product in the union on the market, but when something goes wrong, someone has to pay the

41:22.200 --> 41:23.200
bill.

41:23.200 --> 41:28.080
This is how every system works in all countries.

41:28.080 --> 41:35.240
And what the product liability does tells you who is the liable person and what the

41:35.240 --> 41:39.960
victim has to show to claim the compensation.

41:39.960 --> 41:45.720
So the regime of the PLD exists since 1985.

41:45.720 --> 41:50.800
But as you know, the product of 1985 were not the one that we have today, including

41:50.800 --> 41:55.600
software, AI systems, IoT, et cetera.

41:55.600 --> 42:04.920
So what we have done is to redraft and re-clarify the regime that existed by including all softwares

42:04.920 --> 42:06.200
in it.

42:06.200 --> 42:12.840
Because as you know, and with the example that I gave to you, software can in some situation

42:12.840 --> 42:15.600
cause harm and cause a damage.

42:15.600 --> 42:22.800
So what the PLD does, and it says that the manufacturer is liable for damage caused by

42:22.800 --> 42:25.360
defect in their product.

42:25.360 --> 42:33.760
And the injured person, so in a tribunal or in a court, has to prove the damage, the existence

42:33.760 --> 42:41.600
of the damage, the defect in the product, and the link, what we in legal terms call

42:41.600 --> 42:46.640
the cause of relationship between the defect and the damage itself.

42:46.640 --> 42:52.480
If this is proved, the manufacturer has to compensate the victim or the family of the

42:52.480 --> 42:54.320
victim in case of death.

42:54.320 --> 42:56.680
So the manufacturer is defined.

42:56.680 --> 43:03.520
This is a definition that appears in all legislation, product legislation in the union.

43:03.520 --> 43:06.520
The damage, what damages are we talking about?

43:06.520 --> 43:10.880
Death, personal injury, damage to property.

43:10.880 --> 43:14.880
Think about an IoT boiler system in your house.

43:14.880 --> 43:19.520
Over hits, the house explodes, someone has to pay for that.

43:19.520 --> 43:23.760
That's a simple situation, but at least you see exactly what we're talking about.

43:23.760 --> 43:27.880
Data loss, data corruption, this is a new addition.

43:27.880 --> 43:34.880
So obviously the liability that you had until now covered any physical things, but as you

43:34.880 --> 43:38.840
know, you own stuff, even in the material world.

43:38.840 --> 43:43.840
When you talk about NFTs, why would you be covered if your painting burns because of

43:43.840 --> 43:51.280
your house, the explosion, let's say, or whatever, but you cannot get compensation if actually

43:51.280 --> 43:53.320
you lose your NFT?

43:53.320 --> 43:57.360
So all of this has been re-adapted and included in the regime.

43:57.360 --> 44:02.960
So these are the damages for which the manufacturer has to pay compensation in case there was

44:02.960 --> 44:07.880
a defect that caused the damage to one of them.

44:07.880 --> 44:12.600
So the entire notion of defect, and I'm going to try to explain a bit also what was the

44:12.600 --> 44:22.200
part of the revision, the entire idea of defect is that the product did not, let's say, had

44:22.200 --> 44:27.480
a lack of safety that a general person is expected to have.

44:27.480 --> 44:31.640
So your fire alarm does not detect the smoke.

44:31.640 --> 44:35.600
You are expecting that it would actually do it.

44:35.600 --> 44:43.360
If you have a computer and actually the software has so many vulnerabilities that you lose

44:43.360 --> 44:47.140
any of your data, you might expect that actually should not do it.

44:47.140 --> 44:52.200
So all of these are normally explained in quotes, and if you establish that there was

44:52.200 --> 44:57.400
a defect and that there was damage, then you get compensation.

44:57.400 --> 45:03.280
Defect does not mean that we're talking about a zero absence of bugs in a software, for

45:03.280 --> 45:04.280
instance.

45:04.280 --> 45:05.760
That's not what it means.

45:05.760 --> 45:07.560
Zero, it's impossible.

45:07.560 --> 45:08.900
You cannot have it.

45:08.900 --> 45:15.000
But you can have vulnerabilities that as a developer you should have expected or you

45:15.000 --> 45:16.760
should have foreseen.

45:16.760 --> 45:21.960
So all of these elements are taken into account to establish the liability of the manufacturer

45:21.960 --> 45:27.920
or manufacturer developer depends on which type of product we are talking about.

45:27.920 --> 45:35.000
So as I said, the liability has been revised, there are different adaptations of the regime

45:35.000 --> 45:40.640
for liability, the digital age, circular economy, this is about the substantial modification

45:40.640 --> 45:42.360
that we're talking about.

45:42.360 --> 45:48.400
The global value chains, this is a concept that we talk mostly in trade where a product

45:48.400 --> 45:54.860
comes from outside of the union, the manufacturer is established outside of the union and brings

45:54.860 --> 45:56.200
the product in the union.

45:56.200 --> 45:59.840
So you need to know who is the liable one.

45:59.840 --> 46:03.060
And then a better protection for victims.

46:03.060 --> 46:11.440
So basically what the new proposal or the new product liability directive proposed is

46:11.440 --> 46:17.160
to say that any software is a product, no matter how it's supplied or provided.

46:17.160 --> 46:21.920
So this obviously also includes any AI systems.

46:21.920 --> 46:27.120
No matter if it's a software as a service or anything that will be concerned as a service,

46:27.120 --> 46:32.160
all of them are software and all of them are products and all of them will be covered by

46:32.160 --> 46:34.160
the liability.

46:34.160 --> 46:37.960
But at the same time you also know that software do not work independently.

46:37.960 --> 46:46.000
You have what we call the digital service, the flow of data that feeds the your AI system

46:46.000 --> 46:47.000
for the training.

46:47.000 --> 46:52.600
All of them will be covered and all of the providers of those data, for instance, will

46:52.600 --> 46:57.960
be also covered by the liability in case something goes wrong.

46:57.960 --> 47:02.040
As we talk about already, there is the exception of open source software outside of a commercial

47:02.040 --> 47:03.520
activity.

47:03.520 --> 47:10.120
To be clear, outside of a commercial activity is the exception for any product.

47:10.120 --> 47:14.340
If a product is outside of a commercial activity, it's out.

47:14.340 --> 47:16.280
But what is a commercial activity?

47:16.280 --> 47:22.880
Well, if your software is sold, this is a commercial activity.

47:22.880 --> 47:28.680
If you provide services to the company that takes your open source software, this is a

47:28.680 --> 47:30.200
commercial activity.

47:30.200 --> 47:33.160
Those are examples of commercial activity.

47:33.160 --> 47:36.920
This is how it has been interpreted by the court.

47:36.920 --> 47:42.040
This is part of the court judgments and case law.

47:42.040 --> 47:48.680
You will have different situations, but these are some examples that I gave to you.

47:48.680 --> 47:52.080
The damages to data loss and corruption.

47:52.080 --> 47:54.840
The software updates and upgrades.

47:54.840 --> 48:02.000
Obviously your software or any type of product that are digital evolved during their lifetime.

48:02.000 --> 48:04.280
This has also to be taken into account.

48:04.280 --> 48:10.840
If you do not provide a software update or upgrade that was necessary to avoid the damage,

48:10.840 --> 48:12.800
you can be held liable.

48:12.800 --> 48:18.880
These are the different elements, but obviously I will not go into absolute details.

48:18.880 --> 48:23.920
Addressing the cyber vulnerabilities might also open a claim for damages.

48:23.920 --> 48:31.720
The evolution of an AI system through machine learning could also open a claim if the machine

48:31.720 --> 48:33.600
creates any damage.

48:33.600 --> 48:36.700
So that's a bit of the adaptation.

48:36.700 --> 48:41.560
The circular economy is the general concept of substantial modification.

48:41.560 --> 48:47.400
So obviously if someone substantially modifies a product, in this case a software, it should

48:47.400 --> 48:52.480
be the one who should be held liable if something happens, has a manufacturer or the developer

48:52.480 --> 48:58.680
of this software after he has done the substantial modification.

48:58.680 --> 49:05.600
The value chain is more related to the traders that imports the product in the union.

49:05.600 --> 49:12.520
As a victim you should not be blocked just because you do not know who is the manufacturer

49:12.520 --> 49:13.520
of the product.

49:13.520 --> 49:20.320
So anyone who is part of the value chain that brought the product in the union can be held

49:20.320 --> 49:21.320
liable.

49:21.320 --> 49:28.520
So through an importer, if you buy through an online marketplace, those entities could

49:28.520 --> 49:31.280
be held liable instead of the manufacturer.

49:31.280 --> 49:36.360
And then obviously if they have contract with the manufacturer itself, they can have recourse

49:36.360 --> 49:39.800
against him.

49:39.800 --> 49:48.560
The better protection, it's more for technical points, but it's how it's going to work in

49:48.560 --> 49:50.220
courts.

49:50.220 --> 49:53.480
You have situations that are so complicated.

49:53.480 --> 49:58.240
Let's take an AI system, explaining where the defect is in an AI system might be complex

49:58.240 --> 50:01.140
as a victim to show.

50:01.140 --> 50:06.640
So we created what we called in legal terms legal presumptions.

50:06.640 --> 50:12.400
If you have one of the, if the victim can prove one of those elements, you have what

50:12.400 --> 50:14.040
we call the presumption.

50:14.040 --> 50:19.280
So we presume that the product is defective and it has caused the damage.

50:19.280 --> 50:25.620
And if it's the case, then it is to the manufacturer to explain that actually it is not the case.

50:25.620 --> 50:33.180
So that is a legal tool that exists in every system, but we have adapted it to ensure that

50:33.180 --> 50:38.580
if something goes wrong, someone at least has a possibility to have a claim.

50:38.580 --> 50:41.520
It does not mean that you're liable.

50:41.520 --> 50:48.080
It just means that you can bring a claim to a court and make your case and explain why

50:48.080 --> 50:53.800
the product was defective and why you have a damage and why the manufacturer should be

50:53.800 --> 50:55.120
held liable.

50:55.120 --> 50:57.040
This is not an automatic situation.

50:57.040 --> 51:03.280
It's not because we have included software, for instance, in the scope of the legislation,

51:03.280 --> 51:05.200
that it means that you will be held liable.

51:05.200 --> 51:06.500
You need to have a damage.

51:06.500 --> 51:10.920
You need to have a plane that crashes because of the software that obliged the pilot to

51:10.920 --> 51:14.000
go down instead, to go up.

51:14.000 --> 51:20.080
The autonomous vehicle that goes into a wall, why there was nothing on the road.

51:20.080 --> 51:25.280
Those kinds of situations are the ones that at least allow a victim to make the claim

51:25.280 --> 51:29.280
and go in court and try to get the compensation.

51:29.280 --> 51:34.520
If the product was not defective, well, then there is no problem.

51:34.520 --> 51:41.480
And again, when we talk about software, this is not a zero bug that we're talking about.

51:41.480 --> 51:46.440
We are talking about expectation that you have about the software, the fact that your

51:46.440 --> 51:54.920
software should not overheat your boiler, the fact that the pilot, the software pilot

51:54.920 --> 51:59.120
in your plane should not push down while you're trying to go up.

51:59.120 --> 52:03.520
Those kinds of things, these are the situations that we're talking about.

52:03.520 --> 52:07.160
So these are a bit of technical situations.

52:07.160 --> 52:13.520
But we have what we call a disclosure of information.

52:13.520 --> 52:18.320
Only the manufacturer of the product itself knows the product.

52:18.320 --> 52:27.840
So as a victim, you need to have access to some sort of information, like the data used,

52:27.840 --> 52:34.680
any kind of evidences that could be of an help to create the claim.

52:34.680 --> 52:39.240
Obviously those information are protected by trade secrets.

52:39.240 --> 52:44.800
This is not a way of giving away your secrets.

52:44.800 --> 52:46.360
They are protected through courts.

52:46.360 --> 52:48.280
They are systems.

52:48.280 --> 52:56.680
We have years and years of practice in national system, in tribunal, to know exactly what

52:56.680 --> 53:01.280
can be showed, how can it be showed, and what to protect.

53:01.280 --> 53:08.120
But there should be an access to the necessary information for that.

53:08.120 --> 53:16.760
And finally, this is a bit of the small details that have been changed.

53:16.760 --> 53:22.760
There was a ceiling before for claims, before you could not get more than 70 million.

53:22.760 --> 53:26.840
I mean, we're not talking about every claim will be 70 million.

53:26.840 --> 53:28.600
Let's put it like this.

53:28.600 --> 53:30.480
But there was a ceiling cap.

53:30.480 --> 53:32.080
This has been removed.

53:32.080 --> 53:36.640
Nothing explained that you should limit it in number of money.

53:36.640 --> 53:38.240
There was a threshold.

53:38.240 --> 53:44.840
If your damage was less than 500 euros, you could not have any claim for liability.

53:44.840 --> 53:51.640
And then the liability as a time period, you're not liable for 300 years.

53:51.640 --> 53:57.280
You're liable for 10 years after putting on the market your product.

53:57.280 --> 54:01.840
After that, you cannot be held liable under these rules.

54:01.840 --> 54:04.960
But there is a time limitation.

54:04.960 --> 54:13.520
This allows to predict and to ensure the risk of your business, if it's a business, or of

54:13.520 --> 54:15.680
your product.

54:15.680 --> 54:20.440
And there has been a small adaptation for personal injuries.

54:20.440 --> 54:25.080
This is typical for some specific product like pharmaceutical products where the damage

54:25.080 --> 54:27.280
appears after.

54:27.280 --> 54:33.040
I mean, I didn't go into all the details, but the product liability does not apply only

54:33.040 --> 54:34.280
to software.

54:34.280 --> 54:35.840
It's one of the products.

54:35.840 --> 54:42.080
We're talking about cars, cars, pharmaceutical products, all of them.

54:42.080 --> 54:48.480
So any damage that any of those products will cause, you would have a claim for compensation.

54:48.480 --> 54:51.480
So that's it from me.

54:51.480 --> 54:53.000
Thank you very much.

54:53.000 --> 54:58.920
I hope there was not too technical.

54:58.920 --> 55:02.640
