Now I think it's probably one of the first times that the industry and NGOs really agree.

01:00:17.800 --> 01:00:24.040
So Martin's presentation was very interesting, and I noted down many of the points that we

01:00:24.040 --> 01:00:27.160
also highlight in our position.

01:00:27.160 --> 01:00:32.520
I also want to take a moment to say that you probably wonder, especially the open source

01:00:32.520 --> 01:00:39.320
community, you wonder why the industry, the big tech or multinationals, why do they care

01:00:39.320 --> 01:00:42.360
about the open source community?

01:00:42.360 --> 01:00:47.460
So actually, I just wanted to clarify that for us, it's very, very important to make

01:00:47.460 --> 01:00:52.960
sure that the open source community is not overburdened by this legislation.

01:00:52.960 --> 01:01:00.680
For many of our members, even up to 100% of their commercial products have relied on open

01:01:00.680 --> 01:01:06.200
source components, and just like James said, there are many priorities, many things that

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:11.080
we can improve at the CRA, but not overburdening the open source community is one of our top

01:01:11.080 --> 01:01:12.760
priorities as well.

01:01:12.760 --> 01:01:21.120
So it is also important to note that it's a bit of a stereotype to think that the big

01:01:21.120 --> 01:01:26.400
tech companies, for example, they only rely on closed source and they don't care about

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:31.640
the open source community, but I want to highlight that for us, it is very, very high important

01:01:31.640 --> 01:01:37.320
to make this a key priority for the CRA to have clarity on what this means for the open

01:01:37.320 --> 01:01:38.920
source community.

01:01:38.920 --> 01:01:46.400
So I'm not going to repeat too much myself because you already said it, Recital10 excludes

01:01:46.400 --> 01:01:49.440
open source, and we very much welcome this.

01:01:49.440 --> 01:01:51.640
And in general, we welcome the legislation.

01:01:51.640 --> 01:01:53.080
It's a very good draft.

01:01:53.080 --> 01:01:55.640
It's something we can really work with, and we need it.

01:01:55.640 --> 01:01:56.640
We can start from that.

01:01:56.640 --> 01:02:02.400
We all agree, also the private sector, that we absolutely need these type of requirements.

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:06.720
So we are very willing to find a way together that makes it work, but we really need to

01:02:06.720 --> 01:02:08.240
get it right.

01:02:08.240 --> 01:02:13.080
Including too much, too soon, can also be very damaging.

01:02:13.080 --> 01:02:19.580
So for open source, there is the conundrum of it's excluded, but not really.

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:25.880
So the text says that it's not in, but then when you look at the commercial element of

01:02:25.880 --> 01:02:32.120
it, and if you look at the definition of what commercial is under the blue guide of the

01:02:32.120 --> 01:02:37.520
new legislative framework, it says that commercial is understood as providing goods in a business-related

01:02:37.520 --> 01:02:38.720
context.

01:02:38.720 --> 01:02:42.160
So what does this mean for the open source community?

01:02:42.160 --> 01:02:43.920
What does a business context mean?

01:02:43.920 --> 01:02:50.120
Because like I said before, many of the commercial products rely on open source components.

01:02:50.120 --> 01:02:52.200
So we need clarity.

01:02:52.200 --> 01:02:56.400
Right now, if you look at the document, there are 85 pages.

01:02:56.400 --> 01:02:59.260
Commercial is mentioned only twice, and there is no definition.

01:02:59.260 --> 01:03:05.360
But this brings me to the bigger element, the issue of the proposal that we really see.

01:03:05.360 --> 01:03:10.800
One, we really welcome the fact that the NLF is the approach that is chosen.

01:03:10.800 --> 01:03:17.160
Benjamin did a great job explaining the NLF and the C marking and everything related tangible

01:03:17.160 --> 01:03:18.160
products.

01:03:18.160 --> 01:03:26.360
That is now, the big quest right now is how to move a regime that has been so working

01:03:26.360 --> 01:03:28.680
very well, we think, for tangible products.

01:03:28.680 --> 01:03:33.640
But now, the biggest challenge is the CRA wants to transform this regime into something

01:03:33.640 --> 01:03:40.640
that is workable for software, which is, again, very welcome, because NLF has proven to be

01:03:40.640 --> 01:03:43.840
the right way to do things.

01:03:43.840 --> 01:03:48.760
But we really need to work more on the definitions.

01:03:48.760 --> 01:03:52.080
So commercial is just one way, one example.

01:03:52.080 --> 01:03:54.760
Then there are other examples, like components.

01:03:54.760 --> 01:04:01.680
