01:22:09.480 --> 01:22:14.800
projects because each and every project, except maybe like my hobby project, which I only

01:22:14.800 --> 01:22:20.120
do for myself and publish somewhere, has some economic result, creates value.

01:22:20.120 --> 01:22:23.160
And there will be people using it to create further value.

01:22:23.160 --> 01:22:28.920
And so it is basically very hard to write a non-ambiguous way to tell commercial from

01:22:28.920 --> 01:22:30.160
non-commercial.

01:22:30.160 --> 01:22:33.960
And all projects, including like, I mean, search centers like in the net universities

01:22:33.960 --> 01:22:37.720
need some money to get at least donations.

01:22:37.720 --> 01:22:40.680
So there is no way you can tell this.

01:22:40.680 --> 01:22:43.920
And on the other hand, I would also be against in saying that all open source software is

01:22:43.920 --> 01:22:47.880
exempt from this regulation because I'm sure that the proprietary software makers would

01:22:47.880 --> 01:22:51.560
come and say, you know, as they have been saying for 20 years, open source is just a

01:22:51.560 --> 01:22:55.600
toy, it's just a hobby project, so you should use proprietary software which is secure.

01:22:55.600 --> 01:22:56.680
So don't do that.

01:22:56.680 --> 01:23:01.520
The problem is really that this law doesn't seem to understand how software works.

01:23:01.520 --> 01:23:05.980
I mean, software, pure software, material products have a nature which is significantly

01:23:05.980 --> 01:23:09.160
different than any physical product with software in it.

01:23:09.160 --> 01:23:13.920
So this regulation seems to be designed with cars in demand, with toys, with IoT devices,

01:23:13.920 --> 01:23:15.760
but not for pure software.

01:23:15.760 --> 01:23:18.280
Pure software is more similar to literature in a way.

01:23:18.280 --> 01:23:22.200
It's something that is the result of collective development.

01:23:22.200 --> 01:23:26.880
And if you have a look at open source projects, yes, we are the manufacturers of Davco.

01:23:26.880 --> 01:23:30.400
But if you look at the code, it's written by people everywhere on the planet.

01:23:30.400 --> 01:23:35.400
So yes, but the real authors are maybe like a thousand people which are in Europe, outside

01:23:35.400 --> 01:23:36.880
of Europe, everywhere.

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:41.760
And so your law seems to put the burden of putting a CE mark on every line of code which

01:23:41.760 --> 01:23:43.080
is imported into Europe.

01:23:43.080 --> 01:23:44.960
I don't even know what that means.

01:23:44.960 --> 01:23:46.440
We have repositories.

01:23:46.440 --> 01:23:48.360
Maybe they are in Europe, they are mirrored in the US.

01:23:48.360 --> 01:23:52.000
There are people from Australia and from China putting code into it.

01:23:52.000 --> 01:23:55.640
And this code is traveling all over the world throughout the borders of the European Union

01:23:55.640 --> 01:23:57.760
several times per second.

01:23:57.760 --> 01:24:01.960
So should I every time I check some code, I mean, someone should stop the code at the

01:24:01.960 --> 01:24:03.280
border and put the CE mark.

01:24:03.280 --> 01:24:05.280
This doesn't really make any sense.

01:24:05.280 --> 01:24:07.240
It's simply impossible.

01:24:07.240 --> 01:24:13.240
And it is to say, I mean, all the people here, I mean, your law is designed for the traditional

01:24:13.240 --> 01:24:17.280
20th century way of making things in which there's a manufacturer and there's a distributor

01:24:17.280 --> 01:24:21.440
and someone that sells them in a shop and then there's the use of the consumer.

01:24:21.440 --> 01:24:25.520
I mean, like if we were still buying, sorry, I'm trying to be sure, but I know you want

01:24:25.520 --> 01:24:28.720
to stop me, but I have to say this.

01:24:28.720 --> 01:24:33.840
And so it seems designed for the time when we went to the shop to media markets and bought

01:24:33.840 --> 01:24:36.600
Windows 95 in a box on a CD.

01:24:36.600 --> 01:24:38.560
And this is not how it works.

01:24:38.560 --> 01:24:44.040
Everyone here is at the same time a manufacturer, a distributor, an importer and a user of code.

01:24:44.040 --> 01:24:46.640
And there's no way you can distinguish these roles.

01:24:46.640 --> 01:24:49.080
So you have to find something.

01:24:49.080 --> 01:24:50.080
You have to find somewhere.

01:24:50.080 --> 01:24:52.600
So I know I can cut it short.

01:24:52.600 --> 01:24:56.040
So I don't understand the problem you're trying to solve.

01:24:56.040 --> 01:25:00.160
Show me one case in which a European piece of open source software had a problem that,

01:25:00.160 --> 01:25:05.240
I mean, created issues with the entire world and how this could be solved by this regulation.

01:25:05.240 --> 01:25:09.320
