01:30:21.280 --> 01:30:26.640
us to use the new legislative framework because they are familiar with it from other product

01:30:26.640 --> 01:30:28.120
types, right?

01:30:28.120 --> 01:30:33.040
So we want to ensure that all stakeholders can use the same framework.

01:30:33.040 --> 01:30:36.400
If we now invent a different framework, it will lead to a lot of fragmentation.

01:30:36.400 --> 01:30:39.640
It will make compliance more difficult for companies.

01:30:39.640 --> 01:30:41.120
So that would be difficult.

01:30:41.120 --> 01:30:45.800
Of course, I mean, there's this crucial question of where to draw the line of commercial.

01:30:45.800 --> 01:30:48.280
I think we are open to all your points.

01:30:48.280 --> 01:30:49.520
We understand them.

01:30:49.520 --> 01:30:55.240
I think what would, from our perspective, be very difficult, I mean, this is how I understood

01:30:55.240 --> 01:31:00.320
your intervention, would be to say we just exclude all open source because it's all somewhat

01:31:00.320 --> 01:31:02.560
commercial and it all needs to be excluded.

01:31:02.560 --> 01:31:06.560
I think this would not work simply for the fact because it would create an incentive

01:31:06.560 --> 01:31:11.200
for proprietary manufacturers to switch over to open source, right?

01:31:11.200 --> 01:31:13.960
Not everyone can do that.

01:31:13.960 --> 01:31:14.960
You want that?

01:31:14.960 --> 01:31:15.960
Okay.

01:31:15.960 --> 01:31:16.960
Okay.

01:31:16.960 --> 01:31:17.960
I see.

01:31:17.960 --> 01:31:21.720
No, but it would create an incentive to get out of the scope and to not have to comply,

01:31:21.720 --> 01:31:22.720
right?

01:31:22.720 --> 01:31:24.600
I don't think this is what you want.

01:31:24.600 --> 01:31:29.280
Then there was also a point from you on all the many small players and how it would be

01:31:29.280 --> 01:31:32.400
maybe difficult for them to comply.

