So the cyber resilience act is, I mean, the requirements are risk-based.

01:31:36.620 --> 01:31:40.080
That means that, I mean, when you're a very small player, there's also a chance that maybe

01:31:40.080 --> 01:31:44.920
your project faces smaller risks and is maybe less critical.

01:31:44.920 --> 01:31:50.640
And you can take that into account when you comply with the requirements of the regulation.

01:31:50.640 --> 01:31:57.440
On top of that, for the vast majority of products, we only require self-attestation by the manufacturers,

01:31:57.440 --> 01:32:02.400
which means you will not have to reach out to any third parties or interact with any

01:32:02.400 --> 01:32:03.400
authorities.

01:32:03.400 --> 01:32:05.640
You can do it all by yourself.

01:32:05.640 --> 01:32:08.520
And this should be absolutely feasible.

01:32:08.520 --> 01:32:10.160
What other questions did we have?

01:32:10.160 --> 01:32:17.320
Yeah, there was this question of how the CRA would improve the ecosystem for components

01:32:17.320 --> 01:32:21.480
that are vulnerable, such as log4j, where you said, I mean, this is a non-commercial

01:32:21.480 --> 01:32:22.480
component.

01:32:22.480 --> 01:32:26.560
So, I mean, we have this due diligence obligation in our proposal.

01:32:26.560 --> 01:32:32.280
That means that in the future, when a commercial manufacturer integrates a product, for instance,

01:32:32.280 --> 01:32:37.640
a logging utility that is free of charge available, they will have to make bigger effort than

01:32:37.640 --> 01:32:40.240
today looking at these components.

01:32:40.240 --> 01:32:42.320
I mean, that, again, of course, depends on the risk.

01:32:42.320 --> 01:32:47.600
I mean, if your project is low risk, you will only maybe check the change log if there are

01:32:47.600 --> 01:32:51.280
regular security updates or not, and you're done with this assessment.

01:32:51.280 --> 01:32:55.800
But of course, if you integrate this component into something much more critical, you will

01:32:55.800 --> 01:32:59.720
have to take a much more closer look at these components.

01:32:59.720 --> 01:33:04.400
So what we're trying to do is we're trying to make manufacturers of commercial products

01:33:04.400 --> 01:33:10.440
proprietary or open source or whatever assume more responsibility for the open source components

01:33:10.440 --> 01:33:11.440
that they're integrating.

01:33:11.440 --> 01:33:17.360
And we believe that this will help raise the level of security on these components as well.

